explanation:
For checking MISRA rule about use of string.h functions you must consider any symbol that could (directly or indirectly) use standard string routines on data reachable from this function. Explanations: 
- OS_CHECK_POINTER (macro): expands to pointer-check handling inside this function; may invoke logging/early-return code paths that could use string functions (e.g. formatting). Need the macro to see whether any string routines are used on abs_wakeup_time or other pointers.
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: directly called; its implementation may manipulate object names/tokens or perform string operations on data derived from var_id; must be inspected for any string.h calls and their argument sources.
- OS_CondVarTimedWait_Impl: called when ObjectIdGetById succeeds; its implementation could use string functions on fields of the token or time pointers — must be analyzed.
- OS_printf: the logging/printf implementation is reachable (via the macro or other paths); printf-style implementations or wrappers sometimes use string routines and format arguments — include to check for unsafe uses involving pointers from this function.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, OS_ObjectIdConvertToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: these are internal callees of OS_ObjectIdGetById (per call graph). Any of them might call string.h routines on object/token fields — include to trace uses of pointer data originating from var_id or token.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken, OS_TimeGetTotalSeconds, OS_TimeGetNanosecondsPart: callees of OS_CondVarTimedWait_Impl per graph; include to ensure no string operations occur on token/time fields passed from the target function.
- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: present in the static call graph for this function (test/stub hooks). In unit-test builds these may be invoked and can perform metadata/string handling; include to ensure stubs do not introduce out-of-bounds string accesses using pointers passed from the target.
- OS_object_token_t, OS_time_t, osal_id_t, int32: the type/layout of the token, time, and id are needed to determine whether pointer fields inside them could be passed to string functions and to reason about bounds.
- OS_SUCCESS, OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_CONDVAR: constants/enums used by the function and passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById; include to understand control flow and which code paths in callees are exercised (and thus whether string functions in those paths are reachable).

In short: include the macro, the two direct callees, their internal callees (per static graph), the logging facility, unit-test stub hooks, and the relevant types/constants so the analyzer can trace any uses of <string.h> from this function's inputs/derived data and establish whether they can access out-of-bounds memory.
